				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div></p>
<div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry"><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_lesson-plan151.png" alt="Lesson Plans - The Learning Network" /></a><a title="See all lesson plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/"><img class="w35 right" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_lesson-plan35.png" alt="Lesson Plans - The Learning Network" /></a></p>
<h6 class="kicker">Global History</h6>
<p class="summary">Teaching ideas based on New York Times content.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/category/global-history/">See all in Global History Â»</a></li>
<li><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/">See all lesson plans Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What do you think of when you hear the word âAfricaâ? In this lesson, we seek to challenge preconceptions with articles that offer new perspectives and defy stereotypes. From poverty and war to arts and entertainment, the worldâs second largest continent is far more complex than it may seem &#8212; or than front-page headlines may reveal.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You may wish to begin by surveying studentsâ existing knowledge and interest in Africa. What do they already know or believe, and what topics or issues do they want to learn more about?  Students can use this <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/activities/KWL_NYTLN.pdf">K/W/L chart</a> (PDF) in order to organize their thoughts, leaving the last column open for later reflections.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then dive right into the articles below, using them in any order that you wish. Classes can focus on one or two issues, or use the categories below as starting points for further investigation &#8212; such as through a <a href="//www.jigsaw.org/overview.htm">jigsaw</a> activity, with pairs or small groups conducting research. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-143207"></span></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Africa Is a Place Where: </strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>A) Everyday Life Inspires Musicians and Artists</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In many parts of Africa, artists and musicians are enjoying a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/09/world/africa/african-artists-lifted-by-the-promises-of-democracy-and-the-web.html">new global popularity</a> fueled by economic growth, more democratic governments and fast-spreading connections to the Internet. In this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/africa/100000002637004/a-new-age-for-african-artists-.html">video</a>, members of the Kenyan music collective Just a Band describe how their music has evolved from playful to political after a recent song about human rights went viral.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Across the continent, filmmakers in Nigeria have developed the<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/magazine/nollywood-movies.html"> worldâs third-largest movie industry</a>, &#8220;Nollywood.â  Consumers buy up their mix of comedies, love stories and gangster films for a dollar or two, providing jobs and entertainment that have crossed national borders and even developed new markets in Europe and Asia. See what itâs like behind the scenes in this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/magazine/100000001378151/nollywood-heights.html">video about the film industry</a> in Lagos, Nigeria.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even in parts of Africa where life is hardest, artists find ways to spread a little light and color. Barbers<a href="//lens.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/documenting-west-africa-one-barbershop-at-a-time/"> dress up their shops</a> to compete for customers, and photographers<a href="//lens.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/17/picturing-everyday-life-in-africa/"> document life</a> and find beauty in <a href="//lens.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/01/an-african-journey/">unexpected places</a>. In Abuja, Nigeria, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/10/24/opinion/international/life-with-boko-haram.html">stand-up comics</a> helped to lighten things up during a spate of attacks by the terrorist group Boko Haram.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What do you learn about life in Africa through its art or entertainment that you might not otherwise know? Choose some of your favorite examples from the resources above, and write a review or creative response.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000001378151" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">Nollywood Heights</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">Behind the scenes of Nigeriaâs thriving film industry.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                By Ben Solomon on                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>February 23, 2012.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                            </span>
        </div>

                    <div class="sharetools-video-container">
                <div id="sharetools-video-tools-100000001378151"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-tools">
                    <ul>
                        <li class="sharetool embed-sharetool">
                            <a href="javascript:;" data-share="embed" data-modal-title="">
                                <i class="icon sprite-icon"></i>
                                <span class="sharetool-text ">embed</span>
                            </a>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div id="sharetools-video-inline-100000001378151"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-inline"
                    data-shares="facebook|,twitter|"
                    data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/video/magazine/100000001378151/nollywood-heights.html?action=click&amp;contentCollection=magazine&amp;module=blog-video&amp;region=caption&amp;pgtype=article"
                    data-title="Nollywood Heights"
                    data-description="Behind the scenes of Nigeriaâs thriving film industry."
                    data-content-type="video">
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>B) Poverty Is Shrinking, and Local Economies Are Growing</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sub-Saharan Africa is still the poorest region of the world, as <a href="//data.worldbank.org/topic/poverty#tp_wdi">measured</a> by the percentage of people living in deep poverty. But those numbers have <a href="//povertydata.worldbank.org/poverty/region/SSA">improved</a> considerably since the 1990s, and some economists like Jeffrey D. Sachs see reason to hope for an <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/25/opinion/the-end-of-poverty-soon.html">end to extreme poverty</a> within the next 20 years. From Uganda to Kenya to South Africa, entrepreneurs are creating <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/10/10/the-avon-ladies-of-africa/">new opportunities</a> for people to make a living at jobs involving <a href="//livinggoods.org/">door-to-door sales</a>,<a href="//honeycareafrica.com/"> beekeeping</a> and <a href="//www.solarsister.org/">solar lamps</a>, with female <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/11/world/africa/women-entrepreneurs-drive-growth-in-africa.html">entrepreneurs</a> leading the way.  While there have been<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/03/opinion/nocera-fighting-poverty-and-critics.html"> setbacks</a> in progress toward those goals, experts see<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/10/opinion/africas-economic-progress.html"> positive trends</a> and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/01/opinion/sunday/forget-developing-fat-nations-must-go-lean.html">innovative practices</a> across the continent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On economic growth, some experts see an <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/19/world/africa/19iht-letter19.html">âAfrica Risingâ model</a> in which the continentâs young workforces and improving governance are helping push some nations down the same hard-charging path that East Asian countries followed in the 1970s. Indeed, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/03/26/world/asia/chinese-leader-xi-jinping-offers-africa-assurance-and-aid.html">China</a> and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/14/world/asia/japans-leader-pledges-aid-on-africa-tour.html">Japan</a> are competing to invest in Africa. But others caution that such growth cannot focus simply on <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/05/10/opinion/global/stop-the-plunder-of-africa.html">extracting natural resources</a> or it will fail to help those who <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/11/06/world/africa/behind-those-fast-growth-rates-rising-inequality.html">need it most</a>. In Mozambique, for example, rural farmers have failed to benefit from new investments <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/11/11/world/africa/as-coal-boosts-mozambique-the-rural-poor-are-left-behind.html">in their own back yard</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Construct a chart with three columns: Reasons for Optimism, Reasons for Pessimism and Ways to Improve. Then read the above articles, looking for specific evidence or anecdotes to support each view, along with suggestions on how African leaders &#8212; and outside governments and companies &#8212; should change their practices. What do you believe are the key steps they should take to make their economies work for all citizens?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>C) Conflict Takes Many Forms</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Certainly wars happen in Africa. But what causes them, and can an understanding of those causes help provide a solution or prevent recurrences?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">First, set out your own theory on the major reasons behind war and conflict in Africa. You may wish to use a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/learning/teachers/studentactivity/KWL.pdf">K/W/L chart</a> to organize your thoughts. Then read the articles below, in which longtime observers of conflict in Africa suggest that the obvious explanations arenât always the right ones.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/24/world/africa/archbishop-and-imam-are-united-across-battle-lines-in-central-african-republic.html">&#8220;Archbishop and Iman Are Across Battle Lines in the Central African Republic&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/opinion/south-sudans-tangled-crisis.html">&#8220;South Sudanâs Tangled Crisis&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/12/01/opinion/to-save-congo-let-it-fall-apart.html">&#8220;To Save Congo, Let It Fall Apart&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/01/16/opinion/global/nationalists-or-islamists.html">&#8220;Nationalists or Islamists?&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As a culminating activity, research more deeply into the factors of and possible solutions to another African war. For example, consider these Room for Debate features on war in <a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2014/01/07/preventing-civil-war-in-south-sudan">South Sudan</a> and the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2012/11/29/stabilizing-the-democratic-republic-of-congo">Democratic Republic of Congo</a>.  Sometimes the original causes become obscured, as in this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/04/world/africa/fear-keeps-thousands-on-run-fleeing-south-sudan-ethnic-violence.html">article</a> and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/africa/100000002632601/a-desperate-river-crossing.html">video</a> about ordinary people caught up in the fighting in South Sudan.  What commonalities do you see between these conflicts, and why do you think their causes are sometimes unclear?</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>D) Cellphones Bring Big Changes</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/04/learning/africacellphoneLN/africacellphoneLN-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/04/learning/africacellphoneLN/africacellphoneLN-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/04/learning/africacellphoneLN/africacellphoneLN-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002748907" width="190" height="284" alt="David Bangirana uses a GPS device to get information on sick plants. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2009/10/06/science/06uganda.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="284"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">David Bangirana uses a GPS device to get information on sick plants. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2009/10/06/science/06uganda.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sarah Arnquist</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We think of America, Europe and Asia as technology hubs. But Africa is the worldâs <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/02/05/business/global/microsoft-looks-to-africa-for-mobile-gains.html">fastest-growing region</a> for smartphones, and a place where <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2009/10/06/science/06uganda.html">even farmers</a> use cellular technology to conduct business. Mobile technology is even helping to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/05/14/world/africa/exploring-the-role-of-mobile-technology-as-a-health-care-helper.html">save lives</a>, connecting doctors with far-flung villages. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How can small amounts of technology change life in a rural village or an underdeveloped city? Read these articles and list the ways in which cellphones make a difference. You can also research the effect of other forms of technology in African nations. What might be the next big technological innovation to improve lives, and how can individuals leverage the power of the Internet to generate positive change? Hold a class contest to come up with ideas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>E)  Writers Continue to Make Waves</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was only last year that one of Africaâs<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/03/23/books/chinua-achebe-examined-colonialism-and-masculinity.html"> most acclaimed novelists</a>, Chinua Achebe,<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/03/23/world/africa/chinua-achebe-nigerian-writer-dies-at-82.html"> died</a> at the age of 82. But the continent is producing a steady crop of new writing talent, whose work often provokes wide-ranging discussions that cross national borders. The Kenyan writer Binyavanga Wainaina recently unveiled a âlost chapterâ of his memoir in which he <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/25/world/africa/as-africa-debates-gay-rights-writer-comes-out.html">announced</a> that he was gay. Coming at a moment when nations across sub-Saharan Africa have been debating sexual orientation and gay rights, it was big news. The novelist Yvonne Adhiambo Owuor writes<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/02/books/review/dust-by-yvonne-adhiambo-owuor.html"> unflinchingly</a> of the realities of daily life in her native Kenya, from politics to race. And Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie, a Nigerian novelist, describes a plane trip to America in which a<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/07/opinion/a-flight-diversion.html"> baby was born</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Browse an <a href="//www.african-writing.com/eleven/">online journal</a> of new African writing and find a favorite, or choose one from this South African list of <a href="//www.citypress.co.za/lifestyle/the-10-best-african-writers-who-arent-chinua-achebe/">10 Best African Writers (Who Arenât Chinua Achebe)</a>. Keep a journal of the best writing you find, or form a literature circle with some friends to share new discoveries.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>F)  Politicians Find Themselves Under Scrutiny</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Africa has long experience with official corruption and repression, from allegations of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/14/world/africa/sierra-leone-graft-charges-imperil-care-and-aid.html">stolen aid money</a> in Sierra Leone and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/13/world/africa/dismay-grows-in-zimbabwe-as-underdog-party-tastes-good-life.html">high living</a> in Zimbabwe, to the new president of Kenya, Uhuru Kenyatta, who has been charged by the International Criminal Court with <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/world/africa/kenyatta-sworn-in-as-president-of-kenya.html">crimes against humanity</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What observers have described as unusual, in recent years, is a spate of highly effective leaders who are believed to prefer economic growth or security over full democratic rights and freedoms. Meles Zenawi, the late president of Ethiopia, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/08/22/world/africa/zenawi-exemplified-conflict-between-american-interests-and-ideals.html">won praise</a> from Western governments for his support in the war against terrorism but left prisons<a href="//latitude.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/08/22/death-of-a-strongman/?nl=todaysheadlines&#038;emc=edit_ee_20120823"> âpacked to the seams</a> with suspected political opponents.â Paul Kagame, the president of Rwanda, brought unimagined economic and social improvements but also earned the label ârepressiveâ from critics. He may be <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/08/magazine/paul-kagame-rwanda.html">âthe most complicated leader in Africa,â</a> wrote the Times correspondent Jeffrey Gettleman. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Read about Mr. Zenawi and Mr. Kagame, listing the ways in which they have helped and potentially harmed their countries. Then decide: Is it worth trading democracy and freedom for economics and security? Where should countries draw the line, and should outside powers like the United States do a better job of voicing their concerns?</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>G) Population Growth Fuels Debates</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/10/11/world/africa/11iht-rffafrica11-LN/11iht-rffafrica11-LN-articleInline-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/10/11/world/africa/11iht-rffafrica11-LN/11iht-rffafrica11-LN-articleInline-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/10/11/world/africa/11iht-rffafrica11-LN/11iht-rffafrica11-LN-articleInline-v2.jpg" id="100000002748878" width="190" height="127" alt="Bethlehem Tilahun, founder of SoleRebels, in her factory in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/11/world/africa/women-entrepreneurs-drive-growth-in-africa.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Bethlehem Tilahun, founder of SoleRebels, in her factory in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/11/world/africa/women-entrepreneurs-drive-growth-in-africa.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Michel Temteme for the International Herald Tribune</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Experts <a href="//www.nytimes.com/1994/01/02/world/poor-lands-success-in-cutting-birth-rate-upsets-old-theories.html">used to believe</a> that economic growth alone would lead to a decline in birthrates, but thatâs not happening so far in sub-Saharan Africa, where populations are growing at <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/africa/100000001488374/africas-population-peril.html">alarming rates</a> in many countries. Some say the answer lies with contraception and family planning, though such methods have led to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/11/03/opinion/kristof-the-birth-control-solution.html">controversy</a> among those who are morally opposed to birth control. Others believe only a mix of strategies, including<a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/05/04/can-the-planet-support-10-billion-people/africas-daunting-challenges"> job creation</a>, birth control and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/11/world/africa/women-entrepreneurs-drive-growth-in-africa.html">womenâs empowerment</a> will do the trick.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What do you think? Read the articles above and keep track of the population-control strategies that experts are recommending.  You may wish to check additional <a href="//www.bbc.com/news/magazine-24303537">sources</a> like the <a href="//www.worldwatch.org/nine-population-strategies-stop-short-9-billion">Worldwatch Institute</a> and the <a href="//www.unfpa.org/public/home">United Nations Population Fund</a>.  Then, based on your reading and personal beliefs, write a policy recommendation for world leaders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>H) International Broadcasters Compete for Viewers</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Think you can escape the din of cable news in sub-Saharan Africa? Hardly. Broadcasters like CNN, BBC, CNBC and Sky News are engaged in a <a href="//www.bizcommunity.com/Article/410/15/78925.html">fierce</a> <a href="//www.mbendi.com/indy/cotl/af/p0050.htm">competition</a> for viewers and advertising dollars, with some like CNN offering special <a href="//edition.cnn.com/CNNI/Programs/africanvoices/">Africa-focused programming</a>.  And <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/08/17/world/africa/chinas-news-media-make-inroads-in-africa.html">China is catching up fast</a> with radio, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=user/CCTVAFRICALIVE">television</a> and print offerings that highlight its continent-wide investment push.<br />
âYou would have to be blind not to notice the Chinese mediaâs arrival in Kenya,â said Eric Shimoli, a top editor at Kenyaâs most widely read newspaper, <a href="//www.nation.co.ke/">The Daily Nation</a>, which entered into a partnership with the Xinhua state news agency last year. âItâs a full-on charm offensive.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Watch some of these Africa-targeted news reports and keep a diary of what you learn. Does the news tend to be positive, negative or neutral? What sorts of topics do they highlight? Write a review in which you compare their coverage with that of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/pages/world/africa/index.html">The New York Times</a> or <a href="//www.world-newspapers.com/africa.html">local African newspapers</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>I) Even Pirates Use Offshore Banks</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Judging from films like last yearâs <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/movies/100000002494318/movie-review-captain-phillips.html">&#8220;Captain Phillips&#8221;</a> starring Tom Hanks, Somali pirates rely upon an unsophisticated set of tools to ply their trade &#8212; motorboats, grappling hooks, AK-47s, that sort of thing. So it might come as a surprise to learn that they send much of their ransom money to <a href="//web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/TOPICS/EXTFINANCIALSECTOR/0,,contentMDK:23491862~pagePK:210058~piPK:210062~theSitePK:282885,00.html">banks in Dubai</a>. World Bank researchers found that they operate sophisticated <a href="//www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21588942-new-study-reveals-how-somali-piracy-financed-more-sophisticated-you">distribution networks</a> in which local merchants, middlemen and even cooks play a role, with the pirates themselves generally earning $30,000 to $75,000 each from an average haul of $2.7 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Piracy in the Horn of Africa has <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/01/opinion/global/shutting-down-the-piracy-business.html">already dropped</a> because of increased security precautions, but experts say it will take determined action to stamp it out altogether. Write a list of their recommendations. Then consider writing a letter to a member of Congress or the federal government, in which you suggest the steps leaders should take to make further progress.</p>
<hr/>
<div id="teaching-standards" class="teaching-standards">
	<div class="stndrd-desc">
		<h4>Standards</h4>
		<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This resource may be used to address the academic standards listed below.</p>
		<webonly><a href="#" class="st">View all</a></webonly>
	</div>
	<div class="common-core-standards stndrd hidden">
	<h5><a href="//www.corestandards.org/ELA-Literacy" title="//www.corestandards.org/ELA-Literacy">Common Core E.L.A. Anchor Standards</a></h5>
			<div class="subject">
		<h5>Reading</h5>
		<ul>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>1</strong>&nbsp;<span>Read closely to determine what the text says explicitly and to make logical inferences from it; cite specific textual evidence when writing or speaking to support conclusions drawn from the text.</span></p>
			</li>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>2</strong>&nbsp;<span>Determine central ideas or themes of a text and analyze their development; summarize the key supporting details and ideas.</span></p>
			</li>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>7</strong>&nbsp;<span>Integrate and evaluate content presented in diverse media and formats, including visually and quantitatively, as well as in words.</span></p>
			</li>
					</ul>
	</div>
</div>
<div class="common-core-standards-mp stndrd hidden">
	<h5><a href="//www.corestandards.org/Math/Practice" title="//www.corestandards.org/Math/Practice">Common Core Standards for Mathematical Practice</a></h5>
	<div class="subject">
		<ul>
			<div class="subject">
		<h5>Geography</h5>
		<ul>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>4</strong>&nbsp;<span>Understands the physical and human characteristics of place.</span></p>
			</li>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>10</strong>&nbsp;<span>Understands the nature and complexity of Earth's cultural mosaics.</span></p>
			</li>
					</ul>
	</div>
					<div class="subject">
		<h5>World History</h5>
		<ul>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>44</strong>&nbsp;<span>Understands the search for community, stability, and peace in an interdependent world.</span></p>
			</li>
					</ul>
	</div>
</div>
